NHANES data exploration

Swen Kuh

2022-08-18

We run into singularity issues for models lme1-lme4 (after removing pregnancy indicator (too many missing obs.), secondhand smoke exposure, potassium intake level, smoking tobacco/cigarette and sodium level), and the warning stops for model lme5. However, when using the urine subsample, we run into the same issue again. There is no warning issued after we remove the education variable. But should we? I didnt want to remove sodium level at first (Im interested in the effects) but in the context of MRP, we are more concerned of predicting than inference of the effects?

The data cleaning code is shown at the bottom of the document.

Running the models - lme4

# remove sodium level - no more singularity error -  6786 observations (after na.omit) 
nhmodel_lme5 = glmer(high_bp ~ (1|age) + (1|ethnicity) + gender + (1|educ) +
                       (1|marital_status) + phys_act + overweight + (1|dep_severity) +  
                       (1|BMI_range) + (1|alc_exc) + (1|diabetes) + trb_sleep + 
                       (1|pov_level) , data = nhdata, family="binomial")

                       (1|pov_level) , data = nh_urn_sub, family="binomial")

# MSE
( pred.lme = predict(nhmodel_lme5, type="response") %>% 
  as.data.frame(.) %>% 
  mutate(pred.bin = ifelse(. >= 0.5, 1, 0), 
         truth = as.numeric(nhsub$high_bp), 
         bias = pred.bin - truth) %>% 
  summarise(mse = mean(bias^2)) )
##        mse
## 1 1.358238

# MSE 
( pred.brms = predict(nhmodel)[,1] %>% 
    as.data.frame(.) %>% 
    mutate(pred.bin = ifelse(. >= 0.5, 1, 0), 
           truth = as.numeric(nhsub$high_bp), 
           bias = pred.bin - truth) %>% 
    summarise(mse = mean(bias^2)) )

Data cleaning

# subsample
# insulin
ins = read.xport(here('data/NHANES 2017-20/P_INS.XPT'))

# urine sample
urn = read.xport(here('data/NHANES 2017-20/P_UM.XPT'))

nh_ins = merge(ins, nhdata, by='SEQN') # 4438 obs
nh_urn = merge(urn, nhdata, by='SEQN') # 2988 obs
